## Angular Coding Standards

Full coding standards are defined in `coding-standards.mdc` (always applied).

This rule serves as a quick reference when working in `.ts` files:

- Standalone components only - no NgModules, no `standalone: true` in decorators
- `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in every component
- `input()`, `output()`, `model()` signal functions - no decorators
- `inject()` instead of constructor injection
- `computed()` for derived state, `linkedSignal()` for dependent state
- Native control flow (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`)
- Explicit type annotations everywhere - no `any`
- Access modifiers (`public`, `private`) on every member - no `protected`
- Public signals: `Signal` postfix; private signals: no postfix
